#### Valence versus Oxidation State

Given the inherent ambiguity of the term "valence," &#91;17&#93; other notations are generally favored today. Beyond the lambda notation used in [IUPAC nomenclature of inorganic chemistry], &#91;18&#93; the [oxidation state](/Oxidation_state) provides a much clearer picture of an atom's electronic condition within a molecule.

The [oxidation state](/Oxidation_state) of an atom in a molecule quantifies the number of [valence electrons](/Valence_electron) it has either gained or lost. &#91;19&#93; Unlike valency, the oxidation state can be positive (for electropositive atoms) or negative (for [electronegative](/Electronegativity) atoms).

Elements in a high oxidation state (greater than +4) often correlate with elements in a high valence state ([hypervalent](/Hypervalent) elements), where the valence exceeds 4. For example, in [perchlorates](/Perchlorate) (ClO⁻₄), [chlorine](/Chlorine) forms 7 valence bonds, making it heptavalent (valence 7), and its oxidation state is +7. Similarly, in [ruthenium tetroxide](/Ruthenium_tetroxide) (RuO₄), [ruthenium](/Ruthenium) forms 8 valence bonds, rendering it octavalent (valence 8), with an oxidation state of +8.

However, there are instances where valence and oxidation state diverge for a given atom. Consider [disulfur decafluoride](/Disulfur_decafluoride) (S₂F₁₀). Each [sulfur](/Sulfur) atom is bonded to five [fluorine](/Fluorine) atoms and one other sulfur atom, giving it 6 valence bonds, hence it is hexavalent (valence 6). Yet, its oxidation state is +5. In the [dioxygen](/Dioxygen) molecule (O₂), each [oxygen](/Oxygen) atom participates in 2 valence bonds, making it divalent (valence 2), but its oxidation state is 0. And in [acetylene](/Acetylene) (H−C≡C−H), each [carbon](/Carbon) atom forms 4 valence bonds (one single bond with hydrogen and a [triple bond](/Triple_bond) with the other carbon). Each carbon is tetravalent (valence 4), but its oxidation state is −1.

